This paper deals with the layout of a tree in external memory, which is a classic problem in data structures (cs.DS). The use of external memory suggests that the paper may also be relevant to database systems (cs.DB). The analysis of the worst-case number of block memory transfers required to traverse a path suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the study of algorithms and complexity (cs.AL, cs.CC). Finally, the use of fixed-topology trees and the consideration of worst-case scenarios suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the study of distributed computing (cs.DC).
